Stolen. This piece was stolen from my showroom today. I’m pretty shocked. We are tucked away, upstairs in @thesodaplant. To steal from an artist, in their quiet space, it’s just so violating. I was inspired last year to make the biggest set turquoise pendant that I had ever made. It’s $850 (my one high end, show stopper). It’s been waiting for the right person. A tall, young man was in my studio for half an hour or so, carefully looking at all of my work. He had a tan jacket, beanie cap, blue mask. I checked in with him a few times as I walked around doing other work. I thought he was shopping for the perfect gift. Then he went to leave and we exchanged goodbyes. A short while after he left, I noticed certain things rearranged, a smaller pendant put on the display where this piece was. Panic set in. Feeling so helpless and betrayed. What else is missing? A few other pieces I think. WTF. It’s not like this is an unrecognizable piece. Keep an eye on people, especially this time of year. If you see this piece around, know it was stolen. Maybe share this post if you are local? Thank you. 🖤

Thank you so much for all of your kind words, messages and shares. It’s easy to let an experience like yesterday freeze up my heart. But the warmth and care of our community melts it right back. Doing our best to learn from the lesson, and make improvements. Studio’s open 10-5. ❤️❤️❤️

It happened AGAIN. Today a different young man stole over a dozen gold vermeil pendants, similar to these. Feeling targeted and shaken. Was he friends with the other guy? We filed a police report. You can still swing by the studio to pick up. It’s such a busy time and hard to lose potential in-studio sales but also hard to risk losing more to theft... and to lose sanity over it all. Artemis was the Greek Goddess of wild animals, the hunt, vegetation and of chastity and childbirth. Her character and function varied greatly from place to place but behind all forms lay the Goddess of wild nature who danced, usually accompanied by nymphs in mountains, forests, and marshes. This is the first moment I’ve had this year to be in my sweet lil studio space. I’m on the verge of making new work, which can be both exhilarating and terrifying. It’s a very intimidating moment, sitting down to roll out PMC after months of not working with it. It’s always hard to get your butt back in the chair. Today I super cleaned this space, practiced a little yoga and now I’m sitting down to make...

All the thoughts, all the doubts, all the distractions are there...just gotta get my butt in the chair. Feels good to get my hands in some Precious Metal Clay! For those who don’t know, I’ve been a PMC Artist for 20+ years! Mitsubishi manufacturing co makes it and as of this month they are taking it off the market. Lots of changes and shifts these past few years but never thought one of the main materials I work with would disappear. Def adds a new layer/level of stress! We were all pioneers in this amazing medium and I made a career out of my love for it. Everything changes I guess... I will make what I can, while I can... ❤️

I bought a lot of Precious Metal Clay this month. Knowing it’s going off the market forced me to stock pile what I could. It’s more than I’ve ever had. On the one hand it feels even more precious and stressful. On the other hand suddenly having more of my favorite material than I’ve ever had is  this great gift to myself. Instead of working from scarcity, in this moment I get to work from abundance. Try things. Follow a notion, a whisp of an idea. I don’t take it lightly. It takes so much to carve out the space to do this work. I’m letting this Equinox/Aries Season/New Moon be a catalyst to charge ahead in my making and it feels exciting and empowering. Taking time to stretch my body so I can sit and make. Reveling in my space. Doing what I can with what I can while I can and enjoying each moment. ❤️

I have so much to say about this piece, where to start. I will try to keep it brief for now and go into more depth later. Last year I was invited to be in a special Moon Circle and at our first gathering, there were 7 of us. 7 Sisters...SistArs. One of whom mentioned the Pleiades - in Greek mythology there are the seven daughters of Titans Atlas and Pleione and Zeus turned them into doves and set them into the heavens. I spent time researching the Pleiades which brought me to the Nebra Disk...

The Nebra sky disc is a bronze disc of around 12" diameter and a weight of 5lbs, having a blue-green patina and inlaid with gold symbols (see second photo). These symbols are interpreted as the Sun or full moon, a lunar crescent, and stars (including a cluster of seven stars interpreted as the Pleiades). Two golden arcs along the sides, interpreted to mark the angle between the solstices, were added later. A final addition was another arc at the bottom with internal parallel lines, which is usually interpreted as a solar boat or a rainbow or even the Aurora Borealis.

It features the oldest concrete depiction of astronomical phenomena known from anywhere in the world. In June 2013, it was included in the UNESCO Memory of the World Register and termed "one of the most important archaeological finds of the twentieth century."

So yeah, I needed to make a pendant of the Nebra Disc! Here it is in brass and we will have them in Sterling Silver too! Hope you love this as much as I do! Releasing these on 4/20 for the Solar Eclipse and 1st day of Taurus Season! Now I have to get ready for our Moon Circle, which I’m hosting today!

I guess my thinking is…
How can we operate when there are others around us suffering? 
How can we ignore what’s going on? 
I can’t. 
What if everyone operated by always giving a piece back to our communities? 
How much better a world would we live in if we could function like this?
We lift up others while we rise. 
We do what we can with what we have. 
We take care of, not just ourselves and our families, but our communities…our humanity. 
We can’t live in a bubble… 
Everything is connected and we’re only as healthy as the people around us. 
We’ve seen this with viruses…with floods… we can’t isolate ourselves on a mountain top, disconnected from the world. 
Where will our food come from if it’s all under water? 
Who will buy our wares if they are focused on survival? 
How can we be passionate about what we’re doing when others are struggling? 
How can we be the light when others are in the dark? 
It just makes sense to me to do what we can, when we can. 
To help. 
And giving back feels so good!
Community feels so good. 
Coming together.
This is the way!
This is our chance to live better.
To try to undo the damage done.
We can't trust anyone else to save us.
We don't need to search for other perfect planets.
This one was perfect,
is perfect.
We have to try to save it for each other.
For our children.
Vermont, I love you!
I see you.
I'm doing what I can.

the looming dark

It starts to creep in now
the light changes
back to school
the air begins to cool
the days shorten
the seasonal depression whispers
"it's coming"

but wait
we still have September
and October is beautiful 
there's sweaters
and less sweating 
tea in our mugs
and less bugs
and soup and stews
and hats to look forward to
tall boots 
and dressing in layers
there will still be sun to savor
the air will be crisp and dry
we can pick apples
we can make pie

we get to enjoy 
the firework finale of fall
before the looming dark settles in
before that dark feeling consumes all
I start to feel it right after 
the summer solstice
knowing that that harkens 
an incremental 
decrease in light
every
single 
day
brings us closer 
to more night
but I say to myself
there's two more months 
of summer to be had
it's not so bad
barely noticed
but once summer 
really starts to dash
and school begins
and store displays go from back-to-school to Halloween in a flash
it's so hard to not feel 
the dull, looming 
all consuming dark

I remind myself that Halloween is fun, all about dressing up and sweets
and November 
has Thanksgiving 
with family and feasts
and the Holidays go by 
so fast 
with gifts to get us through
it's mostly January, February, March that's hard to do
and the gloomy looming dark

the day being cut off 
at 4:00 o'clock
the car struggling to start 
the endless 
frigid dark months 
why can't those feel short?
such a struggle 
for those of us 
that don't do winter sports

and then the deep yearning for spring

Meet the Maker: Jennifer Kahn, Jewelry Maker of @jenkahnjewelry. 

“I really loved the utilitarian side of things,” says Jennifer Kahn, sitting on a teal loveseat in her studio/retail space, surrounded by hundreds upon hundreds of her popular jewelry creations, explaining how she got started in her craft. “And why not have the things that are in your day-to-day life, and right in front of you, be beautiful?”

“I don't know why in me there was this desire to make a living from my hands,” she continues, explaining that she started as an English and art major at UVM, and, while she loved writing and poetry, she found she was increasingly attracted to jewelry. Precious Metal Clay had been recently invented, and it turned out that one of the world’s most accomplished artists in the medium, Celie Fago, lived in Bethel, Vermont. So, in 2001, Jen convinced Fago to take her on as an apprentice and also a housemate, working under her for nine years, honing her craft...

“I call them modern relics,” Jen says, describing her style today. “Kind of artifact-like, ancient-inspired but modernized—they're lightweight and yet very wearable.”

There are also some very rich themes that run through her work—chiefly circles. “How many times am I going to make a circle?” she laughs. “But there are infinite ways to—between repetition and texture and color and shape and combination. So I keep working with circles, I keep working with crescents. I am inspired by all things moon and the moon phases…”
